This is an introduction to the MyHDL hardware description language. The focus
is on writing synthesizable hardware. The introduction is based
on a number of examples that illustrates many important aspects of MyHDL. The
idea is that you should go through the examples in number order and read all
the comments in the examples. Run the examples and view the output from them.

MyHDL is just a Python library. A basic understanding of Python is enough
to use it.

MyHDL creates Verilog code and writing MyHDL requires some understanding of
Verilog hardware design. This introduction assumes that you are already
familiar with that. If not I can recommend 'FPGA Prototyping by Verilog
Examples: Xilinx Spartan-3 Version Book by Pong Chu' which you can find online.

MyHDL and Python is a very powerfull combination for writing testbenches but
that is not the focus of this introduction. On myhdl.org you can find more
about this as well as more detailed documentation about MyHDL.

Prerequisites are that you install these packages:
Must install:
  python3
  gtkwave
Recommended:
  yosys
  iverilog
  netlistsvg (intall npm then: npm install -g netlistsvg)

The examples are in the intro directory.

